review:
After really thinking about it, I cannot recommend this game.

Unless you have a solid group of veteran friends (3+ players) you're going to really struggle. That's fine, but I certainly cannot recommend this game to 90% of players. My most successful playthroughs were when I played very conservatively - I don't know about you, but that is not enjoyable in a hack-and-slash genre game. There was no real room for finesse, because the gameplay mechanics were visually confusing and inconsistent with each other.

I feel it's only fair to complain about this game -- please see complaints below :)

My biggest gripe with this game is the visual representation of what the game thinks is happening. In other words, what you see on screen doesn't always show what is truly happening. This is a massive problem when a single mistake or misjudged action can have big consequences. For example:
- you can get hit by a swinging axe that doesn't actually collide with your character model (only the circle on the floor around your character);
- enemies' melee swings don't hit other enemies (which is confusing since projectiles do);
- you take huge damage from explosive projectiles that hit the other side of walls (and impenetrable objects);
- many of the ranged enemies' shoot animations seem to fire slightly "too soon;" and
- gun-totting enemies' melee-swings can hit you well after any forward momentum has stopped.

These things are visually confusing, yet in a game where a single mistake can kill you it is vital that I can rely on what I see on my screen, and a consistent AI logic.

Another big issue for me is that the game mechanics are not intuitive and often are not consistent with each other. Since so much of the game is spent waiting for an opportunity to hit an enemy, I want to be able to rely on the combat logic. For example;
- melee swings don't do friendly-fire, but projectiles do;
- you can trigger a landmine while incapacitated on the ground;
- grabbing a cliff-edge cancels your Ultimate ability;
- bazooka enemies can suddenly appear and fire 1-2 seconds later (there is no object permanence here);
- the interface doesn't show how many more spawns are in a room (yet it does for a boss room);
- the boss rooms seem completely out of pace with the rest of the game;
- explosives hit you from the other side of a wall, yet armor-peircing sniper projectiles don't.

A few more quick things that made the gameplay worse are:
- The 'quick restart' option doesn't give me my starting items loadout:
- you can get stuck on walls very easily; and
- every enemy attack animation is painfully long, which means that half the game is spent standing out of melee range, waiting to keep fighting.

Very funny to play with a few friends!  

We few, we happy few, we band of brothers;
    For he to-day that sheds his blood with me
    Shall be my brother; be he ne'er so vile,
    This day shall gentle his condition;
